anhood. They frame the story (included in its entirety) with chapters that discuss how it encapsulates notions that Taylor learned from the Chicano movement, the farmworkers' union, his community, his father, his mother, and his religion. Taggart gives the ethnography a solid theoretical underpinning by discussing how the story and Taylor's account of how he created it represent an act of resistance to the class system that Taylor perceives as destroying his native culture.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Okt 2021) 0aLabor movementzColoradozAntonitoxHistoryy20th century. 0aMexican American authorsvBiography. 0aMexican American childrenvFiction. 0aMexican AmericansxEthnic identity. 0aMexican AmericanszColoradozAntonitovBiography. 0aPolitical activistszColoradozAntonitovBiography. 0aTrampsvFiction. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / General.2bisacsh1 aTaggart, James M., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780292797857423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780292797857/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK